<article id="node-16988">
<h1 >3.4.5.30 Calculating the Maximum PLS Loan</h1>
<h2>Summary</h2>
<p>The maximum loan available to a person depends on:</p>
<ul><li>the value of the real assets offered as security for the loan, minus any nominated guaranteed amount (<a href="../../../1/1/g/70">1.1.G.70</a>), AND</li>
<li>their age, OR</li>
<li>the age of the younger partner in the case of members of a couple (<a href="../../../1/1/m/120">1.1.M.120</a>).</li>
</ul><p>These points are explained in the rest of this topic.</p>
<h2>Calculating the maximum loan</h2>
<p>The maximum loan available is calculated using the following formula:</p>
<ul><li>Age component amount multiplied by (the value of real assets divided by $10,000)</li>
</ul><h2>Value of real assets</h2>
<p>The value of a person's real assets (<a href="../../../1/1/r/15">1.1.R.15</a>) is always rounded down to the nearest multiple of $10,000. If the value of real assets is LESS than $10,000, the value is taken to be nil.</p>
<h2>Age component</h2>
<p>The age component amount is determined by referring to a table at SSAct subsection 1135A(3). For the purposes of the table, a person's age is defined as their age on their last birthday. The table sets out an age component amount for different ages, which is used in setting a loan limit for every $10,000 of available real assets.</p>
<div class="example">
<p><strong>Explanation:</strong> The age component amount is intended to take into account the risk of debt exposure to the Commonwealth based on the person's current age. It is aimed at ensuring that there will be sufficient real assets secured to repay the loan at the time of recovery.</p>
</div>
<div class="example">
<p><strong>Example:</strong> A 70 year old single person offers a property valued at $180,000 as security for the loan and she wants to retain equity of $80,000. The maximum loan is calculated as follows:</p>
<ul><li>$3,080 multiplied by ($180,000 minus $80,000, divided by $10,000) = $30,800</li>
</ul></div>
<div class="reference">
<p><strong>Act reference:</strong> <a href="https://www.legislation.gov.au/Series/C2004A04121" title="Social Security Act 1991">SSAct</a> section 1135A(3) The following is the Tableâ€¦</p>
</div>
<h2>Age component - members of a couple</h2>
<p>In the case of members of a couple, the age component is defined as the age of the YOUNGER partner on their last birthday. Although the age component is drawn from a single person, each partner's share of the value of real assets is used to work out the maximum loan amount.</p>
<div class="example">
<p><strong>Example:</strong> A couple aged 72 and 68 years of age, offer property valued at $240,000 as security for a loan to each of them. The property is jointly owned by the couple, and they wish to retain total equity of $45,000 each. The younger partner's age is used for the age component, and the maximum loan available for each partner is calculated as follows:</p>
<ul><li>real assets equal $120,000 minus $45,000. After rounding, this comes to $70,000</li>
<li>maximum loan equals $2,850 multiplied by ($70,000 divided by $10,000) = $19,950</li>
</ul></div>
<h2>Maximum loan available</h2>
<p>The maximum loan available to a person is NOT necessarily a fixed amount that is set permanently. The maximum loan available is recalculated once every 12 months. It is done in conjunction with the January or July review, depending on the part of the year in which the person's birthday falls.</p>
<div class="example">
<p><strong>Explanation:</strong> Each year on a person's birthday, the age component amount available to them increases for each $10,000 of real assets they own. This is necessary on equity grounds, as the maximum loan available to different people of the same age and in the same financial position should be the same regardless of how old they were when they commenced participation in PLS.</p>
</div>
<div class="reference">
<p><strong>Act reference:</strong> <a href="https://www.legislation.gov.au/Series/C2004A04121" title="Social Security Act 1991">SSAct</a> section 1135A Effect of participation in PLS - maximum loan available</p>
</div>
